be an index-n Q(i)-central division algebra and Λ be a Z order in D. For any x = 0 ∈ Λ, we have\nProof: We know that Λ 1 has a ﬁnite index inside Λ ∗ . Let us now suppose that a 1 , . . . , a j are some representatives of the factor group Λ ∗ /Λ 1 . We then have that\nAs | det(ψ(xa i ))| ≥ 1, we can multiply each ψ(xa i ) with a constant c i such that |c i | ≤ 1 and det(c i ψ(xa i ) = 1. Clearly |ψ(xa i Λ 1 ) ∩ B(M )| ≤ |c i ψ(xa i Λ 1 ) ∩ B(M )| for all i. According to Theorem 3.1 we then have that\nwhere N 1 is independent of x and M . The last dotted-equality follows now from Lemma 3.3.\nRemark 4.2: We note that all our inverse determinant sum results do work for all orders, but for simplicity we consider maximal ones.\nProposition 4.3: Let D be an index n Q(i)-central division algebra and Λ be a maximal Z-order in D. Then, for n r ≥ n we have\nProof: From the ideal theory of orders we have that if xΛ = yΛ, then x and y must differ by a unit. Therefore we can write\nwhere X(M ) is some collection of elements x ∈ Λ, ψ(x) F ≤ M , each generating a separate (right) ideal\ngenerated by elements in B(M )∩ψ(Λ)). According to Lemma 4.2 we can upper bound the previous with\nUsing the inequality between Frobenius norm and determi- nant, we have\nfor any element x ∈ Λ. Together with Proposition 4.1, this implies that\nwhere T and K are some constants independent of M . The ﬁnal result now follows by substituting this to Equation 4.\nCorollary 4.4: Let D be an index n Q(i)-central division algebra and Λ be a maximal Z order in D. Then, for n r ≥ n\nCorollary 4.5: Let D be an index n Q(i)-central division algebra and Λ be a maximal Z order in D. Then, for n r ≥ n the lattice ψ(Λ) achieves the optimal DMT at multiplexing gain r ∈ [0, 1].\nRemark 4.3: We note here that using the DMT bound we get (in a dotted sense) growth M 2n 2 −2n for the inverse determinant sum of an order of a Q(i)-central division algebra, when n r ≥ n.\nLet us now concentrate on the case where the center