 and denote ψ(Λ) with L. Then, for n r ≥ n/2\nProof: The right side is just Proposition 5.2 and the left side follows from Proposition 2.1.\nExample 5.1: Let us consider an algebra (Q(i)/Q, σ, −3) and an order Λ = Z[i] ⊗ uZ[i], we can see that Corollary 5.4 gives growth M 0 for the corresponding inverse determinant sum. In here we also know that the unit group of Λ is ﬁnite and therefore vol SL n/2 (H) (B(M )) is constant. This is an example where the bound of Corollary 5.4 is tight (in a dotted sense).\nExample 5.2: Let us now consider an algebra (Q(i)/Q, σ, 3). We can easily prove that this is a division algebra, where inﬁnite place is not ramiﬁed. The left regular presentation gives us an embedding to M 2 (C), but Corollary 5.3 gives that the growth of the inverse determinant sum is in the class M 2 .\nRemark 5.1: These two examples underline the fact that two division algebra codes, that have a fairly similar look, might have totally different inverse determinant sums. This suggest that the performance of the codes can also be dramat- ically different.\nThe research of R. Vehkalahti is supported by the Academy of Finland grants #131745 and #252457. During this work R. Vehkalahti was visiting the Department of mathematics, Chaire des structures alg´ebriques et ge´om´etriques at ´ Ecole Polytechnique F´ed´erale de Lausanne.\nThe research of L. Luzzi is supported by the European Union Seventh Framework Programme (FP7/2007-2013) under grant agreement n. PIEF-GA-2010-274765.\nThe authors would like to thank Alexander Gorodnik for answering questions concerning point counting in Lie groups."},"refs":[{"authors":[{"name":"R. Vehkalahti"}],"title":{"text":"Inverse Determinant Sums and Connections Between Fading Channel Information Theory and Algebra"}},{"authors":[{"name":"L. Zheng"},{"name":"D. Tse"}],"title":{"text":"Diversity and Multiplexing: A Fundamental Tradeoff in Multiple-Antenna Channels"}},{"authors":[{"name":"J.-C. Belﬁore"}],"title":{"text":"An Error Probability Approach to MIMO Wiretap Channels"}},{"authors":[{"name":"A. Gorodni"},{"name":"A. Nev"}],"title":{"text":"The ergodic theory of lattice subgroups"}},{"authors":[{"name":"W. Duke"},{"name":"Z. Rudnick"},{"name":"P. Sarnak"}],"title":{"text":"Density of integer points on afﬁne homogeneous varieties"}},{"authors":[{"name":"A. Gorodnik"},{"name":"B. Weiss"}],"title":{"text":"Distribution of lattice orbits on homoge- neous varieties"}},{"authors":[{"name":"A. Gorodnik"},{"name":"J. Reine Angew. Math"}],"title":{"text":"Counting lattice points"}},{"authors":[{"name":"F. Maucourant"}],"title":{"text":"Homogeneous asymptotic limits of Haar measures of semisimple linear groups and their lattices"}},{"authors":[{"name":"V. Tarokh"},{"name":"N. Seshadri"},{"name":"R. Calderbank"}],"title":{"text":"Space-Time Codes for High Data Rate Wireless Communications: Performance Criterion and Code Construction"}},{"authors":[{"name":"J. C. Belﬁore"},{"name":"F. Oggier"}],"title":{"text":"Lattice Code Design for the Rayleigh Fading Wiretap Channel"}},{"authors":[],"title":{"text":"Maximal Orders in The Design of Dense Space Time Lattice Codes"}},{"authors":[{"name":"I. Reine"}],"title":{"text":"Maximal Orders, Academic Press, New York 1975"}},{"authors":[{"name":"D. Tse"},{"name":"P. Viswanath"},{"name":"L. Zheng"}],"title":{"text":"Diversity-multiplexing tradeoff in multiple access channels"}},{"authors":[{"name":"E. Kleinert"}],"title":{"text":"Units of classical orders: a survey"}},{"authors":[{"name":"L. Solomon"}],"title":{"text":"Zeta Functions and Integral Representation Theory"}},{"authors":[{"name":"C. J. Bushnell"},{"name":"I. Reiner"}],"title":{"text":"Zeta Functions of Arithmetic Orders and Solomon\u2019s Conjectures"}},{"authors":[{"name":"C. J. Bushnell"},{"name":"I. Reiner"}],"title":{"text":"Solomons Conjecture and Local Functional Equation for Zeta Functions of Orders"}}]},"file":{"jsonClass":"File","file":"/home/arnfred/Code/trailhead/resources/isit2012/156956592